<subSubSection id="C3076562FF86FFECFEDFBF72FDD5A70A" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA236E9FF86FFECFEDFBF72FDD5A70A" blockId="24.[215,1715,319,2242]" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">
This interesting new species differs from its congeners, and especially from other red-bodied species, such as 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFCABBF4FFBF3AECF" box="[859,1121,377,413]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFCABBF4FFBC8AECF" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1891" box="[859,1114,377,413]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erubescens">C. erubescens</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
Selys, by the deep black terminal segments of the abdomen. The anal appendages are rather similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFE8BBFD5FDA9AD55" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1891" box="[379,571,483,519]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erubescens">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFE8BBFD5FDA9AD55" box="[379,571,483,519]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">erubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the superiors arc black, and there is only one very small interior tooth. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFE03BC2FFC90AD6F" authorityName="M.A. Lieftinck" authorityYear="1940" box="[499,770,537,573]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoogerwerfi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFE03BC2FFC90AD6F" box="[499,770,537,573]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">C. hoogerwerfi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be most nearly allied to 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFA5EBC2FF9A8AD6F" box="[1454,1594,537,573]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFA5EBC2FF9A1AD6F" authorityName="Laidlaw" authorityYear="1915" box="[1454,1587,537,573]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellona">bellona</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
Laidlaw 1), from Mt. Matang, Sarawak, and Mt. Kinabalu (Borneo). It differs from that species in the longer petiole of the wings, 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFE98BD60FE0BAC28" box="[360,409,854,890]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">Ab</emphasis>
in the wings of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFEFABDBDFE19ACFD" authorityName="Laidlaw" authorityYear="1915" box="[266,395,907,943]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellona">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFEFABDBDFE19ACFD" box="[266,395,907,943]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">bellona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
originating well before the level of the cubito-anal cross-vein, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFE2FBA18FD20AB00" authorityName="M.A. Lieftinck" authorityYear="1940" box="[479,690,1070,1106]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoogerwerfi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFE2FBA18FD20AB00" box="[479,690,1070,1106]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">hoogerwerfi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the two veins are coincident, the position of 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFD70BAADFD3CABED" box="[640,686,1179,1215]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">Ac</emphasis>
distal to 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFE7EBAE2FE4BABAA" box="[398,473,1236,1272]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">Ax1</emphasis>
being identical in the two species. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFEDFBB3DFDD6AA7D" authorityName="M.A. Lieftinck" authorityYear="1940" box="[303,580,1291,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoogerwerfi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFEDFBB3DFDD6AA7D" box="[303,580,1291,1327]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">C. hoogerwerfi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs further from 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFC00BB3DFBE3AA7D" authorityName="Laidlaw" authorityYear="1915" box="[1008,1137,1291,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellona">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFC00BB3DFBE3AA7D" box="[1008,1137,1291,1327]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">bellona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the sharply defined, deep black upperside of segments 8 - 1 0 of the abdomen, the distal five-seventh of 7 being also black in colour, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFC4ABB40FBA9AAC8" authorityName="Laidlaw" authorityYear="1915" box="[954,1083,1398,1434]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellona">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFC4ABB40FBA9AAC8" box="[954,1083,1398,1434]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">bellona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the apical segments are gradually and indefinitely obscured. The anal appendages of the two species are very similar, but the inferior pair of 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFCC5BBD7FC27A957" authorityName="Laidlaw" authorityYear="1915" box="[821,949,1505,1541]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellona">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFCC5BBD7FC27A957" box="[821,949,1505,1541]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">bellona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are decidedly longer than those of 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECF993BBD7FEE4A96E" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECF993BBD7FEE3A96E" authorityName="M.A. Lieftinck" authorityYear="1940" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoogerwerfi" status="sp. n.">hoogerwerfi</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
I have compared the type of this new species with two males and two females of topotypical 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFD05B878FCE4A920" authorityName="Laidlaw" authorityYear="1915" box="[757,886,1614,1650]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellona">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFD05B878FCE4A920" box="[757,886,1614,1650]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">bellona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in my own collection and in that of the Michigan Museum, Ann Arbor, from Mt. Kinabalu. 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFB12B8B5F992A9F5" box="[1250,1536,1667,1703]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFB12B8B5FA68A9F5" authorityName="M.A. Lieftinck" authorityYear="1940" box="[1250,1530,1667,1703]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hoogerwerfi" status="sp. n.">C. hoogerwerfi</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
I think, is also remotely allied to 
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFD10B88EFC50A98E" box="[736,962,1720,1756]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFD10B88EFC29A98E" authorityName="Laidlaw" authorityYear="1931" box="[736,955,1720,1756]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pendleburyi">pendleburyi</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
Laidlaw 2), from the hill-country of Perak. It is easily distinguished from that species by its orange face, the absence of black lines on the dorsum of the thorax, and by the bright orangered abdomen. It differs further from 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFC43B96CFB19A82C" authorityName="Laidlaw" authorityYear="1931" box="[947,1163,1882,1918]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pendleburyi">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFC43B96CFB19A82C" box="[947,1163,1882,1918]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">pendleburyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the basal portion of the 7th abdominal segment being red instead of black, in the absence of brown basal annules to the base of 7 -10, and in the short and rounded superior anal appendages, which in 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D6AFF86FFECFD85B9CBFCDFA773" authorityName="Laidlaw" authorityYear="1931" box="[629,845,2045,2081]" class="Insecta" family="Coenagrionidae" genus="Ceriagrion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="24" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pendleburyi">
<emphasis id="B969EAFBFF86FFECFD85B9CBFCDFA773" box="[629,845,2045,2081]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="361">pendleburyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taper toward the apex, being equal in length to the inferior pair.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
